content.problemStatement:
In Java, the `==` operator is used to compare references, not the actual content of the strings. It checks whether two variables point to the same object in memory.

- For String comparison, it checks if both references point to the same memory location.
- If two strings refer to the same object, `==` returns `true`. If they refer to different objects (even if they have the same content), `==` returns `false`.

---

**Example:**
```java
String str1 = "Hello";
        String str2 = "Hello";
        String str3 = new String("Hello");

        // Comparing using '==' operator (references check)
        System.out.println(str1 == str2);  // true - Both str1 and str2 point to the same memory location.
        System.out.println(str1 == str3);  // false - str3 points to a different memory location.

        // Showing reference values (memory locations)
        System.out.println("Memory address of str1: " + System.identityHashCode(str1)); // 705927765
        System.out.println("Memory address of str2: " + System.identityHashCode(str2)); // 705927765
        System.out.println("Memory address of str3: " + System.identityHashCode(str3)); // 312714112

        // Note: You don't need to understand what hashCode is in detail. It is simply a way to print
        // the memory address of an object. You can see that both 'str1' and 'str2' have the same
        // memory address, while 'str3' has a different one, showing how they are stored in different memory locations.
        // Memory addresses may vary for everyone.
```

